> What do you think?

I'm thinking this might be a good way to do it.

It separates the deprecation from the update which covers my main concern.  I think I'd do it just slightly differently.

Do the deprecation as we do now so there is still a `update_placeholder_format` in `Meta.deprecated` this would do the precision/padding stuff as before, remember we then remove these from the format so we don't have them later on (but only set the format if padding or precision are actually user provided).  Also they are deprecated so it is where they should be dealt with.  Then we add your new section `Meta.update_config` which also has `update_placeholder_format` which is where we set the defaults.  So this way formats can be simple eg `{value}` and the module can then set reasonable defaults if it needs to eg `{value:.2f}`

would that work?

@ultrabug Do you have any views on this?

The basic situation is that in a module like sysdata we have placeholders eg `{cpu_usage}` this ends up being a value something like `20.542317173377157` which is obviously stupid as the value to use but gives the user the ability to have as much precision as they want.  A module writer may decide that they want this displayed as `20.54` so `{cpu_usage:.2f}` would do this. but having a default format containing that just looks long/silly and the user setting a custom format just wants to do `format = 'CPU: {cpu_usage}%'` and get expected results ie not the full precision.  If they don't like the default formatting of the number they could still do  `format = 'CPU: {cpu_usage:d}%'` etc.

So the proposed solution would be to have such a module do 
```
class Py3status:

    class Meta:

        update_config = {
            'update_placeholder_format': [
                {
                    'placeholder_formats': {   # dict of placeholder:format
                        'cpu_usage': ':.2f',
                    },
                    'format_strings': ['format'],  # config settings to update
                }
            ],
        }
```
This way it is not part of the deprecation stuff (which feels wrong) but can be done before the module becomes 'live'.  It is also self contained and out of the way.  To be fair I think this is a rare thing that will be done in modules but will still have several users. This is my preferred option.

The other option is to make it much more explicit but that would probably end up being a different interface than just sharing the deprecation one.  eg

```
Py3status:

    def post_config_hook(self):
        self.py3.update_placeholder_format(...)
```

