@marcoabreu +1 to what Chris is saying.  We generally run with OPEN_MP disabled, and I personally have been unable to build a few times with this configuration.  

At a minimum I would like to test an older clang with OPEN_MP disabled.  I would optionally also agree to use a new Clang with OPEN_MP enabled.  I think having both makes sense, but I only feel strongly about the first one.

Some motivation for running both in the future:  We should keep in mind that at some point we'll have to do some CMake work to detect if OPEN_MP is supported on the version of Clang users are compiling with.  When we do start modifying CMake it would be quite nice to catch any errors here.  Proper testing would require you to run both environments, and mistakes can quite easily slip through. (I've made plenty CMake errors like this in the past).

@garth-wells here is the snippets from some of the self-test code that i use which might be helpful:

Say we need to bind code:
```C++
struct BBB {};

struct AAA
{
	virtual void foo(BBB &) {}
	virtual void pv_foo(BBB &) =0;
};
```

then bindings for call-back-structure will be:

```C++
struct PyCallBack_AAA : public utility::AAA {
	using utility::AAA::AAA;

	void foo(struct utility::BBB & a0) override { 
		pybind11::gil_scoped_acquire gil;
		pybind11::function overload = pybind11::get_overload(static_cast<const utility::AAA *>(this), "foo");
		if (overload) {
			auto o = overload.operator()<pybind11::return_value_policy::reference>(a0);
			if (pybind11::detail::cast_is_temporary_value_reference<void>::value) {
				static pybind11::detail::overload_caster_t<void> caster;
				return pybind11::detail::cast_ref<void>(std::move(o), caster);
			}
			else return pybind11::detail::cast_safe<void>(std::move(o));
		}
		return AAA::foo(a0);
	}
	void pv_foo(struct utility::BBB & a0) override { 
		pybind11::gil_scoped_acquire gil;
		pybind11::function overload = pybind11::get_overload(static_cast<const utility::AAA *>(this), "pv_foo");
		if (overload) {
			auto o = overload.operator()<pybind11::return_value_policy::reference>(a0);
			if (pybind11::detail::cast_is_temporary_value_reference<void>::value) {
				static pybind11::detail::overload_caster_t<void> caster;
				return pybind11::detail::cast_ref<void>(std::move(o), caster);
			}
			else return pybind11::detail::cast_safe<void>(std::move(o));
		}
		pybind11::pybind11_fail("Tried to call pure virtual function \"AAA::pv_foo\"");
	}
};
``` 
(this is all generated by https://github.com/RosettaCommons/binder so it a bit more verbose that written by human)

This is a more elegant fix for pybind than the one I posted above:

```C++
template <typename T> struct format_descriptor<T, detail::enable_if_t<std::is_integral<T>::value>> {
    static constexpr const char c = "bBhHiIqQ"[detail::log2(sizeof(T))*2 + std::is_unsigned<T>::value];
    static constexpr const char value[2] = {c, '\0'};
    static std::string format() { return std::string(1, c); }
};
```

